# Git commits (English + gitmoji)

When creating or amending git commits in this repository, follow these conventions.

## Language

- Write the **subject and body in English**, not French.
- Use the **imperative mood** (`Add`, `Fix`, `Update`, not `Added` / `Fixed`).
- Keep the subject concise (about 72 characters max).
- Add a body only when the "why" is not obvious from the diff.

## Gitmoji

- Prefix the subject with **one gitmoji**, a space, then the subject: `:sparkles: Add hero block`.
- Use the shortcode form (`:bug:`), not the Unicode emoji character.
- Pick the most accurate gitmoji; do not stack several emojis.

Common gitmoji for this stack:

| Shortcode | Use when |
| --- | --- |
| `:sparkles:` | New feature, block, component, or capability |
| `:bug:` | Bug fix |
| `:lipstick:` | UI / CSS / visual tweak without new feature |
| `:recycle:` | Refactor without behavior change |
| `:fire:` | Remove code, assets, or dead files |
| `:globe_with_meridians:` | i18n, translations, `.pot` |
| `:wrench:` | Config, tooling, Cursor rules, CI, build scripts |
| `:arrow_up:` | Dependency upgrade |
| `:memo:` | README or documentation only |
| `:art:` | Code structure / formatting without logic change |
| `:rocket:` | Performance or deployment improvement |
| `:lock:` | Security fix |

## Format

```text
:emoji: Short subject in English

Optional body explaining why, not what.
Wrap at ~72 characters per line.
```

## Examples

```text
:bug: Guard main menu location in ThemeFields
```

```text
:recycle: Rename theme identifiers for Collective La Cabane
```

```text
:lipstick: Adjust footer newsletter spacing on mobile

Improves readability when the form stacks on small viewports.
```

## DONT

- No French in commit subjects or bodies.
- No commit without gitmoji prefix (except merge/revert commits generated by Git).
- No vague subjects (`:wrench: Fix`, `:sparkles: Update stuff`).
